## Introduction & Purpose

The **Copilot Swarm Orchestrator** (rebranded as **Swarm Orchestrator**) is a verification‑first multi‑agent system. It transforms GitHub Copilot from a single‑task assistant into a **parallel, auditable, and self‑repairing team of specialists**.  

Every line of code generated is **proven** against concrete evidence before it ever touches the main branch. The orchestrator does not blindly trust the AI – it demands **commit SHAs, test output, and file diffs** as verifiable artifacts.

This document provides a **complete technical specification** of the orchestrator. Because the original tool relies on the Copilot CLI (`copilot -p`), this guide also includes a dedicated section on **adapting the system to run purely within VS Code Copilot Chat**.

---

## Core Architectural Principles

| Principle | Description |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Isolation by Branch** | Every agent works in its own git branch (`swarm/<session-id>/step-N-agent`). Parallel work never collides. |
| **Evidence‑Based Verification** | Agents must **prove** their work. Claims are cross‑checked against commit logs, test results, and file changes. |
| **Self‑Repair with Limits** | Failed steps are re‑attempted up to 3 times with targeted fix strategies. Verification rules are **never weakened**. |
| **Deterministic Quality Gates** | After merge, eight automated checks (regex, AST, thresholds) validate the final code – **no LLM involved**. |
| **Cost‑Aware Scheduling** | Pre‑execution estimates and hard budgets prevent runaway token usage. |

